  "post_content": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Japanese aesthetic values are primarily informed by a fusion of Shinto and Buddhist ideals. Scholars have dedicated their life to explaining Japanese aesthetic principles and the unique national psyche they are informed by. Continue reading for a straightforward look at Japanese aesthetic principles, the lenses through which nature, people and art are viewed in Japan.</p>\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\">Wabi-Sabi (侘 寂):</h4>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Wabi and sabi are two distinct concepts that are often fused to encapture the beauty of things that are &ldquo;imperfect, impermanent, and incomplete&rdquo; (Leonard Koren). Wabi is the idea of understated beauty and shares a particularly strong association with Zen Buddhism. An elegantly shape vase with a crack in it is valued for its wabi; the vase continues to stand despite its crack, prevailing against its ill disposition. In his essay &ldquo;In Praise of Shadows&rdquo; (1933), novelist Tanizaki Jun'ichirō (1886&ndash;1965) describes the beauty of the tokonoma (alcove) in the traditional Japanese teahouse:</p>\n<p><em><img id=\"1544922553448\" class=\" \" src=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/large_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" alt=\"Junichiro_Tanizaki_02\" data-image-large=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/large_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" data-image-medium=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/medium_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" data-image-small=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/small_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" data-image-xsmall=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/xsmall_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" data-image-thumb=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200900/thumb_Junichiro_Tanizaki_02.jpg\" /></em></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>&ldquo;An empty space is marked off with plain wood and plains walls, so that the light drawn into it forms dim shadows within emptiness. There is nothing more. And yet, when we gaze into the darkness that gathers behind the crossbeam, around the flower vase, beneath the shelves, though we know perfectly well it is mere shadow, we are overcome with the feeling that in this small corner of the atmosphere there reigns complete and utter silence; that here in the darkness immutable tranquility holds sway.&rdquo;&nbsp;</em>(20)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The introduction of </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">into the Japanese vernacular predates the introduction of Buddhism to Japan. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Sabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">often comes up in the </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Manyōshū</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #222222; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">万葉集 </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">&ldquo;Collection of Ten Thousand Leaves&rdquo;), the oldest existing collection of Japanese poetry, compiled during the Nara period and held in high regard as a distinctly unique Japanese work. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Sabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">connotes something that has aged well and is a homonym for &ldquo;rust,&rdquo; cementing its association with aged insight. The aesthetic concept of </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> is also connected to the feeling of &ldquo;sabishii&rdquo; (solitary, lonely, sad). Revisiting Tanizaki&rsquo;s &ldquo;In Praise of Shadows,&rdquo; the author clarifies this uniquely Japanese sensibility by explaining that the Japanese &ldquo;do not dislike everything that shines, but we do prefer a pensive lustre to a shallow brilliance, a murky light that, whether in a stone or an artifact, bespeaks a sheen of antiquity...We love things that bear the marks of grime, soot, and weather, and we love the colors and the sheen that call to mind the past that made them&rdquo; (11-12).</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-4368e083-7fff-93bf-9684-eb7951bd0b73\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #1a1a1a; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Zen philosophy outlines seven aesthetic principles for achieving </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Wabi-Sabi: Fukinsei</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (不均斉): asymmetry, irregularity |</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> Kanso</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (簡素): simplicity |</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> Koko </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(考古): basic, weathered | </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shizen</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (自然): without pretense, natural | </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Yugen </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(幽玄): subtly profound grace, not obvious | </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Datsuzoku </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(脱俗): unbounded by convention, free | </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Seijaku</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (静寂): tranquility, silence.</span></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img id=\"1544923386909\" class=\" \" src=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/large_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" alt=\"Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146\" data-image-large=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/large_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" data-image-medium=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/medium_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" data-image-small=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/small_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" data-image-xsmall=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/xsmall_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" data-image-thumb=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-202209/thumb_Shino_chawan_MBA_Lyon_E554-146.jpg\" /></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">A Chawan (teacup) example of wabi-sabi</span></em></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<h4 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Yugen </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(幽玄):</span></h4>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Yugen </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is rooted Chinese philosophical texts where it carries the meaning of &ldquo;dark&rdquo; or &ldquo;mysterious.&rdquo; Sometimes </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Yugen</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> is mistakenly defined as pursuing or representing another world. The principle is rooted in a preference for allusiveness and mystery over more explicit representations.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-75948367-7fff-2267-d58c-066503e14023\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<h4 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shibui </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(渋い):</span></h4>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shibui</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> refers to simple and subtle beauty. The term originated in the Muromachi period (1336-1392), describing a sour taste, a definition it still carries in modern Japanese. Like </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">wabi-sabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">, </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">shibui </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is applicable to a variety of objects and subjects. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shibui </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">differs from </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">wabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">or </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> as </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">shibui </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">objects are not necessarily imperfect, whereas </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">wabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> or </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> objects can exaggerate intentional imperfections. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Shibui</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> tries to find the middle ground between seemingly opposing concepts such as elegance and rusticness.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<h4 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Miyabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (雅):</span></h4>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Miyabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> is one of the oldest Japanese aesthetic ideals and does not share as strong an association to Zen Buddhism as some of the others discussed. Compared to the other ideals, </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">miyabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is rooted more in courtly manners than it is in nature. In Japanese, &ldquo;miyabi&rdquo; is often translated as &ldquo;elegance&rdquo; or &ldquo;refinement.&rdquo; In order to achieve</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> miyabi, </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">the individual must remove any absurdity or vulgarness to achieve a polished grace. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Miyabi </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is strongly associated with the Heian period (794-1185) and the notion of </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Mono no aware</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">, the bittersweet awareness of flux and vulnerability.</span></p>\n<p><img id=\"1544922459003\" class=\" \" src=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/large_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" alt=\"660px-SesshuShuutouTou\" data-image-large=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/large_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" data-image-medium=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/medium_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" data-image-small=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/small_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" data-image-xsmall=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/xsmall_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" data-image-thumb=\"//cdn.traveltripper.io/site-assets/32_913_22011/media/2018-12-15-200701/thumb_660px-SesshuShuutouTou.jpg\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Landscape by Sesshu Toyo (</span>1420-1506,&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 10.5pt; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Rinzai Zen priest and artist)</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<h4 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Iki</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (いき, often written 粋):</span></h4>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-right: -2.043307086614135pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The ideal of</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> iki </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">originated in the Edo period (1603-1868) and is an expression of style that is spontaneous, original and unfussy. In contrast to sometimes stuffy </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">miyabi</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">,</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> iki </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is not overly refined or self-aware, but ephemeral, straightforward and seductive. </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Iki</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> is not found in nature but in the human realm of appreciating natural beauty or the nature of human beings; using</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> iki </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">to describe a person is a very high compliment. Notably, </span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">iki</span><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> did not originate amongst the sheltered upper classes or in the ascetic environment of temples but among the mercantile class of Edo.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>",
